Web services like Google use login credentials to ensure users only have access to the right data.
We can actually implement this itself using cookies. Cookies are small files that are stored on your computer such that your computer can communicate with the server and effectively say, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm an authorized user that has already logged in.‚Äù This authorization through this cookie is called a session.
Cookies may be stored as follows:
GET / HTTP/2
Host: accounts.google.com
Cookie: session=value

Here, a session id is stored with a particular value representing that session.
